<paragraph blockId="21.[442,862,137,193]" box="[553,745,169,193]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">
(
<figureCitation box="[561,736,169,193]" captionStart="Figures 28–30" captionStartId="20.[138,207,1113,1132]" captionTargetBox="[191,1130,133,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-150@20.[191,1132,133,1077]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figures 28–30. Procerodes plebeius and Uteriporus pacificus? (28) P. plebeius, V.Pl. 954.2, photomicrograph of penial papilla. (29) U. pacificus?, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus (from Poljakova, 1991: figure 15B; labels adapted according to current terminology). (30) U. pacificus, specimen BC 7-5 (ZMA), photomicrograph of horizontal section of the receptacular duct; anterior to the left." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221483" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221483/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Figures 29, 30</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[125,380,250,274]" box="[125,380,250,274]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">
<emphasis box="[125,380,250,274]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Comparative discussion</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[125,1173,299,1685]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[125,326,299,323]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova (1991)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned a presumably new species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sluys &amp; Kawakatsu" authorityYear="2005" box="[810,922,299,323]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,922,299,323]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Uteriporus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Avachinska Bay and the 
<collectingRegion box="[304,357,331,355]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="Gulf" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Gulf</collectingRegion>
of Kronotski, on the east coast of Kamchatka, and from the Komandorskyi Archipelago, namely 
<taxonomicName authority="Sluys &amp; Kawakatsu, 2005" authorityName="Sluys &amp; Kawakatsu" authorityYear="2005" box="[556,668,363,387]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[556,668,363,387]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Uteriporus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[677,743,363,387]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The preserved specimens measured 5–9× 
<quantity box="[195,267,396,420]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
, with rounded front and hind end. Dorsal surface red-brown, ventral surface pale. The posterior gut trunks fuse in the hind end of the body. Testes numerous, distributed between the gut diverticula and occurring throughout the body length. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[302,512,493,517]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, the oviducts fuse posterior to the male copulatory apparatus to form a common oviduct, which subsequently gives rise to three ducts (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 28–30" captionStartId="20.[138,207,1113,1132]" captionTargetBox="[191,1130,133,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-150@20.[191,1132,133,1077]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figures 28–30. Procerodes plebeius and Uteriporus pacificus? (28) P. plebeius, V.Pl. 954.2, photomicrograph of penial papilla. (29) U. pacificus?, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus (from Poljakova, 1991: figure 15B; labels adapted according to current terminology). (30) U. pacificus, specimen BC 7-5 (ZMA), photomicrograph of horizontal section of the receptacular duct; anterior to the left." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221483" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221483/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Figure 29</figureCitation>
): two receptacular ducts, opening into the anterior copulatory bursa, and the female genital duct that communicates with the atrium. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[855,1056,590,614]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova (1991)</bibRefCitation>
, common oviduct and female genital duct are penetrated by shell glands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[125,1173,299,1685]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">
In our opinion, Poljakova’s reconstruction of the female copulatory apparatus most likely is not fully correct. In the two species of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Bergendal, 1890" authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[739,1054,688,712]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[739,851,688,712]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Uteriporus</emphasis>
Bergendal, 1890
</taxonomicName>
that have been described up to the present, the posterior, expanded portions of the receptacular ducts do not communicate directly with the female genital duct. The swollen portions of the receptacular ducts only receive a short, narrow branch of the oviduct before the latter communicates with the female genital duct (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergendal D" box="[670,857,818,842]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" pagination="1 - 123" refId="ref8706" refString="Bergendal D. 1896. Studier ofver Turbellarier. II. Om byggnaden af Uteriporus Bgdl jamte andra bidrag till trikladernas anatomi. Kongliga Fysiografiska Sallskapets i Lund Handlingar Ny Foljd VII: 1 - 123, pls I - VI." type="journal article" year="1896">Bergendal 1896</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 1, figure 4; 
<bibRefCitation author="Sluys R" box="[1037,1169,818,842]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref9110" refString="Sluys R. 1989. A Monograph of the Marine Triclads. Rotterdam and Brookfield: A. A. Balkema. XII + 463 p." type="book" year="1989">Sluys 1989</bibRefCitation>
: figures 101–104). In her reconstruction, 
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[633,839,850,874]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova (1991)</bibRefCitation>
may have been misled by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tomkiewicz W &amp; Ball IR" box="[125,497,882,906]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" pagination="464 - 466" refId="ref9464" refString="Tomkiewicz W, Ball IR. 1973. Uteriporus vulgaris Bergendal, 1890, a marine triclad new to North America. Journal of the Fisheries Research Board of Canada 30: 464 - 466." type="journal article" year="1973">Tomkiewicz and Ball’s (1973)</bibRefCitation>
description of the copulatory apparatus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Bergendal, 1890" authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[1043,1172,882,906]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
Bergendal, 1890
</taxonomicName>
, since she bases her description of this species on the account of these workers and reproduces their reconstruction figure of the copulatory complex (incorrectly, Poljakova refers to Ball, 1973). However, Tomkiewicz and Ball’s reconstruction is incorrect in that it describes a direct connection between the expanded portions of the receptacular ducts and the female genital duct, as already noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sluys R &amp; Ball IR" box="[769,1029,1045,1069]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" pagination="3 - 10" refId="ref9173" refString="Sluys R, Ball IR. 1983. On the status and identity of Procerodes warreni (Girard, 1850) (Turbellaria, Tricladida, Maricola). Mitteillungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin 59: 3 - 10." type="journal article" year="1983">Sluys and Ball (1983)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[125,1173,299,1685]" lastBlockId="22.[138,1185,984,1330]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="465" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">
On the basis of 
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[358,581,1078,1102]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova’s (1991)</bibRefCitation>
description it is difficult to decide whether her specimens from the Far East represent 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[580,702,1110,1134]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[580,702,1110,1134]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[718,847,1110,1134]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[718,847,1110,1134]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or a third, new species. For 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[125,260,1142,1166]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[125,260,1142,1166]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a light brown or reddish brown dorsal surface was reported, which is in agreement with the Kamchatkan specimens, while the dorsal body surface of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[1048,1172,1175,1199]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[1048,1172,1175,1199]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
varies from milky white to pale brown. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[675,804,1207,1231]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[675,804,1207,1231]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the posterior sections of the receptacular ducts may be expanded to greater or lesser extent and thus may approach the generally smaller expansions in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[498,628,1272,1296]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[498,628,1272,1296]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as well as those reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[972,1172,1272,1296]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova (1991)</bibRefCitation>
for the Russian animals. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Sluys R" box="[571,723,1304,1328]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref9110" refString="Sluys R. 1989. A Monograph of the Marine Triclads. Rotterdam and Brookfield: A. A. Balkema. XII + 463 p." type="book" year="1989">Sluys (1989)</bibRefCitation>
, diagnostic features for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[1000,1129,1304,1328]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[1000,1129,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the testes occupying the entire dorso-ventral space (contrasting with the ventral follicles in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[125,249,1369,1393]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[125,249,1369,1393]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the absence of an anterior copulatory bursa (contrasting with the welldeveloped bursa in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[363,488,1402,1426]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[363,488,1402,1426]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Unfortunately, 
<bibRefCitation author="Poljakova AA" box="[701,904,1402,1426]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" refId="ref8966" refString="Poljakova AA. 1991. Tricladida maricola in the Seas of the USSR / White Sea, Black Sea and Far Eastern Sea. Unpublished student report, University of Kazan, Chair of Invertebrate Zoology, 57 p. (in Russian)." type="book" year="1991">Poljakova (1991)</bibRefCitation>
does not describe the vertical dimension of the testes, but a photomicrograph of a histological section (her figure 16A) seems to suggest that a testis follicle extends considerably towards the dorsal body surface. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[253,381,1499,1523]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[253,381,1499,1523]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the receptacular ducts fuse to form a common duct that opens to the exterior, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[358,479,1531,1555]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[358,479,1531,1555]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they open into an anterior bursa that subsequently opens to the outside. It must be noted that re-examination of the 
<typeStatus box="[833,882,1564,1588]" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[1038,1172,1564,1588]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="21" pageNumber="464" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[1038,1172,1564,1588]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed that the receptacular ducts do not merely fuse to form a common duct but expand before uniting and/or open into a small expansion (
<figureCitation box="[729,851,1629,1653]" captionStart="Figures 28–30" captionStartId="20.[138,207,1113,1132]" captionTargetBox="[191,1130,133,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-150@20.[191,1132,133,1077]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figures 28–30. Procerodes plebeius and Uteriporus pacificus? (28) P. plebeius, V.Pl. 954.2, photomicrograph of penial papilla. (29) U. pacificus?, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus (from Poljakova, 1991: figure 15B; labels adapted according to current terminology). (30) U. pacificus, specimen BC 7-5 (ZMA), photomicrograph of horizontal section of the receptacular duct; anterior to the left." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221483" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221483/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="464">Figure 30</figureCitation>
). In the Russian specimens there seems to be an anterior bursa, which is suggested in Poljakova’s reconstruction drawing (
<figureCitation box="[248,366,984,1008]" captionStart="Figures 28–30" captionStartId="20.[138,207,1113,1132]" captionTargetBox="[191,1130,133,1075]" captionTargetId="figure-150@20.[191,1132,133,1077]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figures 28–30. Procerodes plebeius and Uteriporus pacificus? (28) P. plebeius, V.Pl. 954.2, photomicrograph of penial papilla. (29) U. pacificus?, sagittal reconstruction of the copulatory apparatus (from Poljakova, 1991: figure 15B; labels adapted according to current terminology). (30) U. pacificus, specimen BC 7-5 (ZMA), photomicrograph of horizontal section of the receptacular duct; anterior to the left." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5221483" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5221483/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="465">Figure 29</figureCitation>
) but also in a series of photomicrographs of serial sections (her figure 17). However, it must be noted that her reconstruction is not drawn to scale and that the photomicrographs show a distinct duct leading to the second, anterior gonopore. Such a duct is present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="? Sluys" authorityYear="1989" box="[361,493,1080,1104]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="22" pageNumber="465" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="pacificus">
<emphasis box="[361,493,1080,1104]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="465">U. pacificus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bergendal" authorityYear="1890" box="[651,776,1080,1104]" family="Uteriporidae" genus="Uteriporus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tricladida" pageId="22" pageNumber="465" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis box="[651,776,1080,1104]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="465">U. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there is only a short and shallow opening of the anterior bursa to the exterior (cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bergendal D" box="[723,913,1113,1137]" pageId="22" pageNumber="465" pagination="1 - 123" refId="ref8706" refString="Bergendal D. 1896. Studier ofver Turbellarier. II. Om byggnaden af Uteriporus Bgdl jamte andra bidrag till trikladernas anatomi. Kongliga Fysiografiska Sallskapets i Lund Handlingar Ny Foljd VII: 1 - 123, pls I - VI." type="journal article" year="1896">Bergendal 1896</bibRefCitation>
: pl. 4, figure 32; 
